:"1140","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","after about 1173":"after about 1173","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1209":"1209","after 1201":"after 1201","1219":"1219","Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Lallaing, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Lallaing, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]},{"name":"Forest","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name for someone who lived in or by an enclosed wood, Old French <i>forest</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon I de Forest de Lalaing, Seigneur de Lalaing was born in 1165, in Lallaing, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Gerard II de Forest de Lalaing, was 30 and his mother, Adelaide de Raches, was 26. He married Richesente de Landas in 1186. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. He died in 1209, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1165–1209":"1165–1209","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","–1197":"–1197","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–1201":"–1201","–1219":"–1219","1135–1187":"1135–1187","1140–1173":"1140–1173","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","1197":"1197","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","after about 1173":"umbes pärast 1173","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1209":"1209","after 1201":"pärast 1201","1219":"1219","Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Lallaing, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Lallaing, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1165–1209":"1165–1209","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","–1197":"–1197","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–1201":"–1201","–1219":"–1219","1135–1187":"1135–1187","1140–1173":"1140–1173","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","1197":"1197","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","after about 1173":"noin 1173 jälkeen","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1209":"1209","after 1201":"1201 jälkeen","1219":"1219","Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Ranska","Lallaing, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Lallaing, Nord, Hauts-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"1165–1209":"1165–1209","1160–Female":"1160–Décédée","–1197":"–1197","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","–1201":"–1201","–1219":"–1219","1135–1187":"1135–1187","1140–1173":"1140–1173","1165":"1165","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","1197":"1197","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","after about 1173":"après environ 1173","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1209":"1209","after 1201":"après 1201","1219":"1219","Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Valenciennes, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Lallaing, Hauts de France, Nord, France":"Lallaing, Nord, Hauts-de-France, France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Simon I de 